                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Latrissa wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">The addition of new servers and greater bandwidth pipes into those servers almost certainly has eaten into the manhours that they would probably have been using to get content patch and fixes of game mechanics into place.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I've worked in product and program management positions related to software development.  In all but very small efforts, the role of individuals is highly compartmentalized.  Server / database people are not the same group as the content developers.  The patch group is the same thing.
<br />

<br />
I don't buy for a second that people charged with getting new content out the door are working on server issues.
<br />

<br />
The "weak link in the chain", if there is one, is going to be QA in this case.  Still, even this doesn't excuse the undocumented class changes - or the exhalted faction issue (you can buy other race's mounts, but you can't).  In the end, QA is the easiest department to ramp up, because anyone can be a tester.  Art designer?  This week you're playing the game to test function of x, y, and z.  As long as you're not testing your own code, it's OK.  Not optimal for sure, but what's falling through the cracks are gameplay issues (broken quests, etc).  These are things that have to be tested in-game, things you can't reliably write a test program to check.
<br />

<br />
In my view, the failures seem to be taking place at an overall managerial or organization/communication level.  Communication between the devs and the CSRs on the boards is weak at this point.  Either that or the CSRs just aren't following up.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
