                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I agree workcrews are very compartmentalized on a large project, but this is in fact why it is so difficult to track down what is causing a piece of software to crash.  You first need to figure out if it is indeed the server, or the incompatibility between the softward and hardware.  Then on hardware, is it the user end PCs incompatibility, or the server?
<br />

<br />
Recently WoW pinpointed one problem for the game crashing was a boat ride.  The server setup people might have worked in vain for hours trying to figure that one out.
<br />

<br />
Friend of mine who has a world-wide distribution in one of his products recently told me his crew finally tracked down why their machine broke down every day at 5 am as one of their customers complained bitterly.  It turned out to be the room where the machine was placed, and the air conditioner in that room is automatically turned off at midnight, so by 5 am the machine over-heated each night.  WoW has servers in many different physical locations  They would need to track that too.
<br />

<br />
It does take time away from all departments when something like this happens, because my friend told me they tried everything in their software, hardware, test, server and local service department to finally figure out the problem.  In a case like this, I would think the 5 am thing is a dead giveaway something is wrong at that site, but companies tend to have test procedures that are pretty comprehensive in order to catch everything.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
