                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Nokei wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />

<br />
In the end, QA is the easiest department to ramp up, because anyone can be a tester. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Umm... no? Proper testing needs a dedicated group, it can be small but they NEED to be left to their own methodology if they are going to find issues with software builds. You cannot just grab any person and sit them down, and say "OK, click that icon, if it makes a blue glowy, it's a Pass, if not it's a fail". Think of all the times that changes to spells in EQ broke bard songs - seemingly unlreated code! Testing groups need the ability to not only to test what should be working, but to also test what should NOT be working, and to ensure that doing the "don't do that" stuff doesn't cause problems. Just "testing to Pass" is the reason so many things get through QA departments, because PPM demands that they test only what was changed, only test what the change should do, and "hurry up we're already committed to schedule".  <img src="images/smiles/icon_rolleyes.gif" alt="icon_rolleyes.gif" border="0" /></span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><br>
