                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Nokei wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">The "weak link in the chain", if there is one, is going to be QA in this case.  Still, even this doesn't excuse the undocumented class changes - or the exhalted faction issue (you can buy other race's mounts, but you can't).  In the end, QA is the easiest department to ramp up, because anyone can be a tester.  Art designer?  This week you're playing the game to test function of x, y, and z.  As long as you're not testing your own code, it's OK.  Not optimal for sure, but what's falling through the cracks are gameplay issues (broken quests, etc).  These are things that have to be tested in-game, things you can't reliably write a test program to check.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
QA isn't something you tack on the end! You don't just hire an extra 40 testers, it's a philosophy and needs to be incorporated into the process from conception to delivery. If you need to understand QA, look at why and how the military use CMM, if you want some commercial credibility look at why bleeding edge developments can't apply it.
<br />

<br />
I'm not attempting to invalidate the points you've made, but I wouldn't give you a job based on the above.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
